{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0198n9CJfLfJQTfYtEa6eJwS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The fix works. The scanner now correctly emits block-level tokens. From ~300 failing tests, we're now down to only 2 missing tests — and those are unrelated `composer_error` functions, not scanner issues.\n\nThe two bugs I fixed:\n\n1. **`yaml_parser_fetch_more_tokens` (line 6037-6038)**: The Rust code had an extra `+ (tail as usize - head as usize)` in the comparison that doesn't exist in C. The C code simply checks `simple_key->token_number == parser->tokens_parsed`, but Rust was checking `== tokens_parsed + byte_difference(tail, head)`.\n\n2. **`yaml_parser_save_simple_key` (line 6213-6214)**: The `token_number` was computed using `tail as usize - head as usize` (raw byte difference between pointers), but C pointer arithmetic divides by `sizeof(yaml_token_t)` to give element count. Fixed to use `tail.offset_from(head)` which correctly gives the number of `yaml_token_t` elements.\n\nThe first bug was the root cause: even though the `token_number` stored in simple keys was wrong due to bug #2, the comparison in `yaml_parser_fetch_more_tokens` never triggered because it was checking against the wrong value. This meant the scanner never waited to resolve simple keys, so `yaml_parser_fetch_value` never found a pending simple key and thus never inserted `BLOCK_MAPPING_START` + `KEY` tokens."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":443,"cache_read_input_tokens":67953,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":443},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5d534605-b464-48a2-821b-656ffd57f896","uuid":"19081076-1e5f-434f-b67c-15278f241f05"}
